Res Publica Solaris wrote:is thread dead? thread must not die

Another cliché I see everywhere on NS FT empires (and unfortunately in most soft "science" fiction) is the Feudalism IN SPACE trope. Like, if everything else progressed, why has the political de-evolved back into the nightmare of the dark ages?


To be fair, though, it's entirely possible for some aspects of a society's advancement to move in a certain direction while other aspects move in a different direction. For instance, human history in general sees growing technological progress (though the speed at which it grows may change), while political liberalization tends to swing up and down; increasing as any certain civilization becomes controlled by the politics of money, and then decreasing as the power of money fades away in that civilization's imperial stage of life. The idea that "liberal democracy is inevitable in the future" is just another utopian eskhatology that doesn't deserve to be seriously considered.

by Holy Federation of Stars » Thu Jul 08, 2021 5:03 pm

Res Publica Solaris wrote:is thread dead? thread must not die

Another cliché I see everywhere on NS FT empires (and unfortunately in most soft "science" fiction) is the Feudalism IN SPACE trope. Like, if everything else progressed, why has the political de-evolved back into the nightmare of the dark ages?

To satisfy the nerd in me, I will say that traditional Western European Feudalism, what most in the west commonly think of when we think of Feudalism, is probably not possible in a FT context - yes. That system of landownership where land is granted rather than owned, a class of hereditary knights control military affairs, and peasants pay tithes to the church would not work in an FT nation because it was designed to work for a pre-industrial society where the majority of the population was illiterate, impoverished, and worked on farms.

However, this does not necessarily mean that any form of Feudalism is impossible. If we expand the definition of feudalism to mean "hierarchical society where local warlords/rulers pay homage to a centralized state in the form of taxes, but are otherwise able to do their own thing", then that very well might be our future if we manage to escape our solar system. Space is vast, and it's easier to - lets say - entrust the colonization of Alpha Centauri to a solar governor who maybe pays taxes every one-in-awhile, but otherwise is able to do his/her/xer's own thing because it takes weeks, months, if not years for supplies, manpower, etc to reach Alpha Centauri. And if democratic protocols aren't enforced somehow, that "Colonial Governor" could very well turn themselves into a dictator if they so desire - even long after the planet becomes sustaining enough to allow for large-scale democracies like those seen in Europe. And then boom, you have yourself a feudal lord working on behalf of the President/Prime Minister/Chancellor of Earth.

And as Mechyridia somewhat pointed out, that example is assuming that by the time this hypothetical happens, western ideals of liberalism and republicanism are the mainstream on Earth. In a 100 years time, Earth could undergo a radical political shift, ending the democracies and dictatorships of today and replacing them with something we consider bizarre - but is totally normal for them. And if this new political system runs similarly to what we consider feudalism, then there you go.

by Ceranapis » Thu Jul 08, 2021 5:14 pm

Mechyrdia wrote:The idea that "liberal democracy is inevitable in the future" is just another utopian eskhatology that doesn't deserve to be seriously considered.


And even Francis Fukyama of "The End of History" fame doesn't believe this anymore.

Also I think Foundation and especially Dune bear a lot of the blame for Feudalism in Space Trope. Foundation was highly inspired by Decline and Fall of The Roman Empire, and as I remember Dune is feudalism in space. Feudalism made sense in Dune because of how their society restricted technology, but later works inspired by the series didn't always take the same effort. At any rate, both made a huge impact on the SciFi world, and so other authors copied the themes until they became a part of the shared cultural consciousness, and so people replicate those tropes/cliches whether they're aware of them or not.

The worst NS cliche, IMO, are the Wehraboos. They're either 2edgy4me or just plain boring, and in either case, I don't find them fun to play with or engage with. The German-inspired countries that are based on Austria/The Habsburgs, or the Hansa, or Bavaria, or the EU, are more unique, almost always better thought out or written, and I enjoy seeing them. But open any thread and it's a surprise when a Prussian-inspired country doesn't show up. Folks, there's more to German culture (and there was more to Prussian culture) than wanking about military tech.

The cliche I don't really understand are the nations that seem like they'd rather be playing a different game. The ones that spend a really long time writing a factbook about the country's leader and then write like nothing about the society that they govern, often times, they make an anime portrait of the leader. Whatever floats your boat I guess, and they don't bother me like the Wehraboos do, but why are you playing NationStates if you seem to really want to create a character and not a country?

by Valentine Z » Thu Jul 08, 2021 6:01 pm

Plus, it's a point of fascination to look at someone's very evaluate work and see what they respond to what they don't respond to.

For me, I like characters, yes, but I also like writing about a nation and the general characteristics (pun unintended) of it. I like geography, demographics, culture, and the economy stuff, BUT make me do politics and legislation, and I will start fizzing out. Ironically, I came to the political simulation game to not talk about politics eventually.

by Fahran » Thu Jul 08, 2021 6:08 pm

You can use character-driven role-play to explore broad social themes and conventions in a visceral and emotionally compelling way. It's one thing to tell people your society is exceedingly patriarchal. It's another to show them through interactions between likable and well-rounded characters.

In general, stories that have fleshed-out characters interest me a good deal more than simple world-building or bland exposition. That said, I probably spend a little too much time on characters and constructing elaborate networks of extended kinship. The latter does serve to illuminate a few major points about the tension between tradition and modernization in Fahran though, so I suppose it has thematic weight.
